Ese Myth: Ìwòrì sat at the crossroads of genesis and asked: "Of all the light that pours from Ogbe, what deserves to live?" It closed nine thousand eyes and kept only one. But Ṣàngó did not bless the remaining eye — he struck it with fire until it learned to weep. "Attention born from genesis is not passive," thundered the king. "It is the wound that chooses what to remember." The eye that does not weep does not see; it merely records.

Prescription: Your first attention shapes all that follows. Choose your first sight as you would choose your death — deliberately, irreversibly, with full knowledge of what you thereby blind yourself to.

